  <h2>Why mock it up instead of screenshotting the real thing</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>You control the answer.</strong> The real model rarely produces the exact response your slide needs on the first try. A mockup says precisely what you want.</li>
    <li><strong>No private data.</strong> Real screenshots leak chat history, your name, and sidebar content. A mockup shows only what you type.</li>
    <li><strong>Clean framing.</strong> No browser chrome, no awkward crop, no cursor. Export at screenshot resolution, ready to drop into a deck.</li>
    <li><strong>Theme match.</strong> Pick light or dark to match your slides — instead of whatever the app happened to be set to.</li>
    <li><strong>Repeatable.</strong> Need five example exchanges for a course? Script them all in one sitting.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What you'll need</h2>
  <p>
    Just a browser. We'll use <a href="/fake-chatgpt-conversation-generator">Easy Chat Maker's free ChatGPT conversation generator</a> — it runs entirely in your browser (nothing you type is uploaded to a server), and exports clean PNGs and MP4 clips with no watermark.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 1 — Open the editor and pick ChatGPT</h2>
  <p>
    Head to the <a href="/editor?platform=chatgpt">editor with ChatGPT preselected</a>. You'll see a live preview in the middle, a script panel on the left, and settings on the right — platform, light/dark theme, and device.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 2 — Script the exchange</h2>
  <p>
    Instead of coaxing the real model, you write both sides of the conversation as plain text — one line per message, like a screenplay. Use a name for the person (the prompt) and "ChatGPT" for the assistant:
  </p>
  <pre><code>Me: Summarize our Q3 launch plan in 3 bullet points.
ChatGPT: Here's a concise summary of your Q3 launch plan:

• Ship the mobile app to beta users by August 15
• Run the paid acquisition test across 3 channels in September
• Publish the case-study page and open general availability October 1
Me: Great. Now rewrite it for a non-technical exec.
ChatGPT: Absolutely — here's an exec-friendly version...</code></pre>
  <p>
    Hit <strong>Generate Chat</strong> and the preview fills in instantly, styled exactly like the ChatGPT interface — prompt bubbles on the right, responses on the left with the copy, thumbs and regenerate action icons underneath. There's no limit on length, so you can build a full multi-turn conversation, not just a single prompt and reply.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 3 — Polish the details</h2>
  <p>These small touches are what make a mockup read as real:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Edit in place:</strong> click any message in the preview and type to fix wording.</li>
    <li><strong>Theme:</strong> light or dark mode — match your slides or the look your audience recognizes.</li>
    <li><strong>Formatting:</strong> keep responses looking like real AI output — short intro line, bullet points, a closing offer to help further.</li>
    <li><strong>Length:</strong> trim to what fits your slide. A tight 2–3 turn exchange reads better on screen than a wall of text.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Step 4 — Export a screenshot (PNG)</h2>
  <p>
    Tick the consent box (you're confirming the conversation is fictional), then hit <strong>Export PNG</strong>. You get a crisp, high-resolution image of exactly what's in the preview — no watermark, no branding, sized like a real screenshot. Drop it straight into Keynote, PowerPoint, Google Slides, a Notion doc or a blog post.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 5 — Or export an animated clip (MP4)</h2>
  <p>
    For a demo video or a tutorial, <strong>Export Video</strong> renders the exchange as an animated MP4 — the prompt appears, the assistant "thinks", and the response types out just like the real interface. It's a clean way to show a flow on a slide or in a screen recording without a live model going off-script.
  </p>

